Part 4: HTML5 Input Types Knowledge
Question 1: list and briefly explan Five Html5 input that were not available in older HTML version.
ANSWERS:

SEARCH:The element is a container for parts of a document of application perfporming a search of filtering operation

NUMBER:it is specifically intended for entering numbers, such as age, quantity, or height 

RANGE: it is a set of voltage that an analog input channel can digitize with the specified accuracy.

COLOR:it can refer to two main things : either the color space of footage when it's first captured

DATE:the purpode of this element is to allow the entry of a date range

QUESTION 2
What are the adveantages of using HTML5- specific input types (like email, date number) instead of just type="text" for everything

YOUR ANSWERS:

1)New type attributes like email, url, date, time, number, range, tel, and color provide specialized input fields. This offers better user interface elements (e.g., date pickers, color pickers) and automatically triggers appropriate virtual keyboards on mobile devices, improving data entry.

QUESTION 3:WRITE AN HTML CODE FOR EACH OF THE FOLOWING INPUTS WITH APPROPRIATE ATTRIBUTES

ANSWERS:

DATE INPUTE:
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Date Input with Range Restriction</title>
</head>
<body>
    <label for="eventDate">Select a date between January 1, 2024, and December 31, 2025:</label>
    <input type="date" id="eventDate" name="eventDate" min="2024-01-01" max="2025-12-31">
</body>
</html>

A NUBER INPUT:
<label for="age">Age:</label>
<input type="number" id="age" name="age" min="18" max="100" value="25">

A RANGE SLIDER:

<input type="range" min="50" max="500" value="250" class="slider" id="myRange">

PART6 :QUESTION 1:what is difference between the NAME attribute and the ID attribute

ANSWERS:

 name :Multiple form controls within the same form can share the same name attribute, particularly in cases like radio buttons, where a group of options needs to be treated as a single choice.

 ID:The id attribute provides a unique identifier for an HTML element within the entire document. It is used for client-side scripting (JavaScript) to target and manipulate specific elements, and for styling with CSS.

 QUESTIONS 2:
 Explain the purpose of the LABEL element and why it's important for form accessibiliy.

 ANSWER:
 The HTML label element connects form input fields with readable text that explains their purpose.

 QUESTION: what is the difference between radio buttons and checkboxes? when would you use each one? provide and example scenario dor each

 ANSWER:
 Radio buttons are for selecting a single, mutually exclusive option from a group, while checkboxes are for selecting one or more independent options from a list. Use radio buttons when only one answer is possible (like choosing a gender), and use checkboxes when multiple selections are allowed (like choosing pizza toppings).  


